<HEADLINE>
FT  16 FEB 94 / International Company News: Northwest Airlines drops
first-class seats
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Northwest Airlines, the fourth biggest US carrier, and its European partner
KLM Royal Dutch Airlines yesterday joined the growing number of
international airlines to abolish first-class travel.
Passengers using the two airlines will now have a choice between only two
classes of service: economy class, and a premium service called world
business class, an upgraded version of the old business class service.
The main feature of the service will be a seat pitch (the distance between
seats) of 48 inches, giving passengers about 25 per cent more legroom than
other airlines offer in conventional business class cabins. The usual
business class seat pitch is 38 - 40 inches.
The only airlines offering more room to business class passengers will be
those that have already abolished first-class travel - Virgin Atlantic of
the UK and Continental Airlines of the US, both of which have seat pitches
of 55 inches.
Airlines are moving towards the abolition of first-class accommodation
because of the proportion of fare-paying passengers using it has declined in
the cost-conscious 1990s. Many people occupying first-class seats are
airline employees or passengers enjoying complimentary upgrades.
Carriers believe they can make more money from their aircraft by merging
first class with business class and filling the space with passengers
attracted by higher levels of comfort and service.
</TEXT>
