<HEADLINE>
FT  16 FEB 94 / International Company News: Regulators lift strict
supervision of Citicorp
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Citicorp announced yesterday that federal banking authorities have agreed to
end their strict regulatory supervision of the large US banking group. The
decision is likely to pave the way for Citicorp to reinstate its dividend,
which has been suspended since late 1991.
The strict regulatory surveillance - known as a memorandum of understanding
 -was imposed on Citicorp by the New York Federal Reserve and the
Comptroller of the Currency in February 1992. At the time, the bank was
burdened with billions of dollars of bad loans, and Citicorp was one of
hundreds of, mostly smaller, US banks that had agreed to accept
exceptionally broad surveillance by industry regulators.
Among the restrictions imposed by the special agreement with regulators,
Citicorp was not allowed to make acquisitions or add to its assets without
the approval of the federal authorities. Also, the bank did not declare a
dividend while the agreement was in force.
The bank is expected to announce its first dividend payment on its common
stock to shareholders in 2 1/2 years. Analysts suggest this could happen as
early as the end of the current quarter.
Citicorp will be able to consider the acquisition of other banks. Although
the group is not believed to be planning any such moves in the immediate
future, Mr John Reed, Citicorp chairman, told employees that capital was
available for the bank's growth.
While the lifting of the memorandum of understanding will not effect the
day-to-day operations of the bank, it is a recognition that regulators are
satisfied with Citicorp's financial position.
In the past two years, the bank's management has worked hard to restore
Citicorp's health, slashing costs, beefing up its reserves, selling assets
and writing off bad loans. During that period the bank has benefited from
low domestic interest rates, which have widened the margin between the
interest it pays on its funds and the interest it earns on its loans, and an
improvement in the condition of the US commercial property market. The bank
is now considered well capitalised by regulators, and last month Citicorp
announced record annual profits of Dollars 2.2bn for 1993.
</TEXT>
