<HEADLINE>
FT  16 FEB 94 / International Company News: Institutions pay FFr403 a share
for Elf
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Institutional investors in the privatisation of Elf Aquitaine, the large
majority of which are European, will pay FFr403 (Dollars 68.3m) a share in
the oil group, according to the French economy ministry.
The price, determined through a process of book-building, is largely in line
with market expectations. It compares with FFr385 for the public issue and
yesterday's closing price of FFr424.
As with the public issue, which was three times subscribed, the tranche
allocated to institutional investors received strong demand, according to Mr
Edmond Alphandery, the economy minister.
However, the imposition of a clawback option meant that the 27m Elf shares
originally allocated to institutional investors were reduced by 20 per cent.
Of the institutional tranche, about 26 per cent of the shares will go to
French groups and 45 per cent will go to other European investors. US
institutions will receive about 22 per cent of the shares. Combining the
institutional and the public offer, about 73 per cent of Elf's shares sold
on the market will be in French hands.
The total proceeds to the state, including the market issues, the sale of
shares to a group of long-term stable investors and the tranche for Elf
employees, is expected to bring receipts of about FFr35bn. Mr Alphandery
said the smooth sale of most of its 51 per cent stake in Elf, which is due
to be followed by the sale of Union des Assurances de Paris, put the
government well on course to achieve its target of FFr55bn from
privatisation receipts this year.
With the exercise of the clawback option, individual investors will receive
a total of 38.6m shares, although most will be still be alloted fewer than
they ordered. Applicants for between 10 and 30 shares will receive the first
10 shares ordered and some extra shares in line with the amount requested.
</TEXT>
