FT  16 FEB 94 / Observer: Knight's turn
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Ruth Dudley Edwards' conclusion, in her history of The Economist, that
'nobody ever got the last word in a debate with Andrew Knight', is spot on.
The executive chairman of News International had been asked, along with
several other former editors of The Economist, to sign the frontispiece of a
first edition of Edwards' history, one of several books, including an uncut
first edition of Pope's Rape of the Lock from Mary Moore, which have been
donated to a fund-raiser for St Anne's College, Oxford. Jeffrey Archer bangs
the gavel at Middle Temple Hall on February 23.
But whereas Sir Alastair Burnet, Rupert Pennant-Rea and Bill Emmott just
signed their names, the self-made millionaire has glued copies of both his
reviews of Edwards' book inside the front cover.
