<HEADLINE>
FT  16 FEB 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In the last episode of Middlemarch on BBC2 the air is full of the sound of
chickens coming home to roost. Raffles the blackmailer returns and falls ill
at Bulstrode's. Dr Lydgate attends for medical reasons but is also looking
to Bulstrode for money to avoid bankruptcy. Rosamond is determined to leave
rather than suffer the stigma of poverty, but is found by the saintly
Dorothea in compromising circumstances with heart throb Ladislaw. Vintage
Palmolive (9.30).
That is preceded by the outstanding spoof The Day Today which ridicules the
pretensions and mannerisms of news and current affairs television by
imitation, exaggeration, and the unexpected (9.00).
BBC1 begins its six part series on 'professional' crime in Britain since
1945, The Underworld (9.30). Today's programme features 'Mad' Frankie Fraser
who has spent 40 years in prison, Eddie Chapman, said to be the first man in
Britain to blow safes with gelignite, and burglar George 'Taters' Chatham
who stole the Duke of Wellington's swords from the V &amp; A Museum .
</TEXT>
