FT  16 FEB 94 / Threat to miners' gala mounts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The survival of the Durham Miners Gala, Britain's biggest and most evocative
annual working-class rally, looked further in doubt yesterday after the
Durham Miners Association executive concluded that it could not afford to
finance the event this year.
Faced with the demise of the Durham coalfield and the consequent loss of
income, it is to appeal to the trade union and Labour movement to try to
stage this year's 110th gala.
The northern region executive of the Trades Union Congress will discuss the
appeal today.
Mr Dave Hopper, general secretary of the association and the National Union
of Mineworkers' north-east area, said after yesterday's meeting that if this
year's gala were held, it would constitute a 'dignified end'.
At issue is not only the Pounds 20,000 needed to mount the Durham city event
but its identity as a socialist rally to the left of the present Labour
leadership. In earlier years it staunchly promoted Labour policy. But the
party leader has not attended since 1987.
In spite of the gala's emotional resonance, it looks improbable that other
unions will provide unconditional funding.
Mr Bob Howard, northern TUC secretary, said: 'If it was to be without
control of the mainstream TUC and Labour movement, it's unlikely that would
be acceptable.'
