<HEADLINE>
FT  16 FEB 94 / Teaching science is unpopular career
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A shortage of good science and technology teachers is predicted today by the
the independent National Commission on Education.
In a survey to be published next month the commission found that only 10 per
cent of students expecting to earn a first-class honours degree had applied
for jobs in teaching, compared with 27 per cent of those in line for
third-class honours.
Teaching was least popular among science students, with only 5 per cent of
engineering and technology students opting for education as a career.
Mr Josh Hillman, the report's author, said: ''Teaching is not popular among
those for whom there is the greatest need within the profession.'
He said the survey, which contacted 1,400 final-year students, raised
serious concerns about the types of students choosing to go into teaching,
although it did not yet indicate a crisis in overall numbers.
Although vacancies for teachers are at an all-time low, educationalists
believe there could be a teacher shortage when the economy emerges from
recession.
Insights into Education and Training will be published on March 2 by the
National Commission on Education.
