<HEADLINE>
FT  16 FEB 94 / Housing recovery aids NHS funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The recovery in the housing market has enabled health authorities to raise
additional funds by selling unwanted hospital sites to builders.
Barratt, Britain's third-largest housebuilder, and Watford-based Country &amp;
Metropolitan Homes yesterday announced a joint Pounds 100m development plan
at Highlands Hospital at Enfield, north London, which is to close. The
hospital services will be transferred over the next three years to the
nearby Chase Farm hospital.
The land has been bought by the developers from the New River Health
Authority.
Country &amp; Metropolitan said that outline planning permission to construct
about 1,000 homes and community facilities had been 'granted in principle'
by Enfield Borough Council.
As part of the agreement with the council the company has been asked to pay
Pounds 1.8m towards a new junior and infants school.
There are plans to refurbish some of the older Victorian hospital buildings
as private-sector flats and social housing for the Metropolitan Housing
Trust.
A rise in new-house sales last year prompted builders, which had run down
their stock of land during the recession, to resume buying development
sites.
Hospitals which have large tracts of unwanted land, due to a switch in
emphasis in the health service away from hospitals to community-based care,
have been natural targets for house-builders.
Commercial property developers are also expected to show interest in some of
the large city-centre hospitals earmarked for closure in London and
elsewhere.
Housing land prices in southern England, where a number of hospitals are
threatened with closure, have risen by up to a quarter since the beginning
of last year.
</TEXT>
