<HEADLINE>
FT  16 FEB 94 / 112 jobs lost as Du Pont announces plant closure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Du Pont, the US-owned chemicals and energy company, announced a plant
closure yesterday with the loss of 112 jobs, and the sale of another smaller
unit.
The plant is one it bought from ICI in an international asset-swap deal last
July. The company said its decision to close the compounding plant at
Billingham, Cleveland, which makes nylon-based plastics, was due to the
tough economic environment which had severely affected prices and made it
necessary to reduce excess capacity so as to remain competitive.
Mr John Newbold, Teesside district secretary of the TGWU general union which
represents most of the workers who lost their jobs, attacked both Du Pont
and ICI and said he felt a sense of betrayal over the closure.
He said there was a developing trend in the European chemicals industry in
which assets were concentrated on a few large producers, who then shut
plants to reduce overcapacity.
The 112 job losses are the second tranche announced by Du Pont in plants
acquired when it took over ICI's European-based nylon business in return for
its own US acrylics business, plus about Pounds 235m.
Three months after the deal was clinched in mid-1993 Du Pont announced it
was shedding 1,100 of the 5,300 ICI employees taken on under the transfer.
All but 150 of the 1,100 jobs lost were in the UK.
Du Pont also announced the sale of the Verton nylon long fibre compound
business yesterday, also at Billingham, to LNP Plastics Nederland BV, a
Dutch-based subsidiary of Kawasaki Steel Corporation.
A condition of the deal, which has yet to be concluded, is that the plant
and its 26 employees must be relocated off ICI's Billingham site. Du Pont
said it hoped the plant would move elsewhere in Teesside.
Du Pont is retaining its three other compounding plants in the Netherlands,
Belgium and Germany.
</TEXT>
