<HEADLINE>
FT  16 FEB 94 / Training funding attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Government funding policies have encouraged a dramatic fall in the number of
training places for the most disadvantaged, including the long-term
unemployed and people with disabilities, according to a study from the
National Council for Voluntary Organisations.
The charity, in a letter to Mr Michael Forsyth, minister of state at the
Department of Employment, has asked for a full-scale review of funding which
it says discriminates against the recruitment of the most disadvantaged on
to government-funded training programmes.
Training and enterprise councils, which administer government training
schemes including the scheme for adults, Training for Work, are being paid
according to the volume of qualifications their trainees attain. This can
encourage them to recruit on to schemes those who are likely to get
qualifications in the shortest period of time.
According to the charity the long-term unemployed made up 50 per cent of
those on Employment Training (now called Training for Work) in January 1990.
This had fallen to 37 per cent in September 1993. Entrants from ethnic
minority groups had fallen from 12 per cent of the total to 11 per cent
while disabled entrants had fallen from 12 per cent to 11 per cent. Cuts of
up to 10 per cent in budgets for Youth Training, the training scheme for
young people, are being forecast by some Tecs as they begin negotiations
with the Department of Employment.
Tecs had been aware of proposed cuts to the budgets of Training for Work but
the cuts in YT were not anticipated.
</TEXT>
