   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, has stepped up his
campaign for more effective industrial and trade associations by criticising
the Engineering Employers' Federation and the Confederation of British
Industry for failing to merge their central functions.
Mr Heseltine, in a speech at the federation's biennial dinner in London last
night, said 'turf battles and power struggles' had overwhelmed the two
organisations.
The federation said earlier this year that plans for a merger of the two
organisations' central functions had been abandoned. But it is now
discussing a more limited arrangement that could produce an alliance with
the CBI's National Manufacturing Council in areas where they overlap.
Last year Mr Heseltine said his department wanted to talk to a limited
number of 'lead' associations that would represent wide areas of industry.
Last night he said he had been impressed by the number of trade associations
that had come forward to help address the key issues of Britain's
competitiveness. The DTI had to select the associations that could deliver
the ability to gauge competitiveness.
'We will not talk to those that can't,' he said.
Referring to similar attempts to forge unity in the engineering professions,
Mr Heseltine said Sir John Fairclough, chairman of the Engineering Council,
had 'spent an age' in an as yet unsuccessful quest to create unity from 45
institutions in an initiative to give the professions some clout.
