<HEADLINE>
FT  16 FEB 94 / SIB asks if market practice is sharp practice
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN and MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Last summer investment bank SG Warburg outraged institutional investors when
it asked the Stock Exchange to prevent big shareholders driving down the
price of British Telecommunication shares just before it auctioned the
government's final stake in the company.
The Stock Exchange considered the request but backed down after institutions
accused it of helping to create a false market in BT shares.
The dispute illustrates the problems confronting regulators eight years
after the institution of benchmark legislation for the securities industry
and for investor protection.
Since then dramatic changes have overtaken the UK equity markets. There has
been explosive growth in the use of derivative instruments; new techniques
for raising equity finance have been adopted; foreign participants now play
a leading role in market making and new trading systems challenge the
traditional monopoly of the Stock Exchange.
Yesterday the Securities and Investments Board, the City's chief regulator,
released a discussion paper asking whether some market practices, while
aiding the profitability of some participants, were undermining the market.
In particular, SIB is asking whether there is enough transparency of
transaction for investors to know whether they are paying the right price
for shares. It also asks whether there is enough transparency for derivative
instruments based on those shares to reflect their value accurately.
The paper asks whether some of the exchange's potential competitors, such as
Tradepoint, benefit from the centralised market which it creates and ought
to be required to contribute to its costs.
Mr John Kemp-Welch, who will become chairman of the Stock Exchange in July,
has identified such competition as the single greatest challenge facing the
exchange.
SIB's paper asks whether the sort of short selling that institutional
investors engaged in before the BT3 offering is a form of market
manipulation and whether measures should be introduced to limit the practice
or make it more visible.
Mr Andrew Large, SIB's chairman, acknowledges that significant commercial
interests are at stake. For instance, marketmakers are not required to
disclose the prices at which they agree to buy and sell large blocks of
shares to each other via inter-dealer brokers' screens, to which access is
restricted.
Mr Roger Barton, managing director of business development at the London
Financial Futures Exchange, said SIB's suggestion that those screens should
no longer be restricted 'is the most important part of the SIB report'.
He said Liffe had pressed the Stock Exchange in recent months for access to
those prices. While the number of transactions made through the inter-dealer
brokers' screens was not great, the value was significant. Without access to
those prices, which tended to be inside the prices quoted on the exchange's
own Topic screen, derivatives could not accurately reflect the cash markets
they were intended to mimic.
Another Stock Exchange rule which allows marketmakers to obscure the true
value of securities is one which allows a 90-minute delay before the
publication of any transaction in any stock which is three times its 'normal
market size'.
Marketmakers have argued that they should be allowed to hide the prices for
the largest share purchases they undertake until they have reduced their
risk either by selling the shares to a third party or through the use of
derivatives.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9651 Regulation of Miscellaneous Commercial Sectors.
    P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
    P6221 Commodity Contracts Brokers, Dealers.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>MKTS  Market data.
    COSTS  Equity prices.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
