<HEADLINE>
FT  16 FEB 94 / MPs put financial regulation under the microscope: Roland
Rudd and David Wighton on the parliamentary probe into a system that is
supposed to protect investors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD and DAVID WIGHTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The first detailed parliamentary scrutiny of the regulation of financial
services since the establishment eight years ago of the Financial Services
Act begins today.
Against a background of controversy over the mis-selling of personal
pensions and home-income plans, MPs from the all-party Commons Treasury and
civil service committee believe the timing of their inquiry could not be
better.
During the next five months the committee will take evidence from the
existing self-regulating organisations, the fledgling Personal Investment
Authority, the Securities and Investments Board, and Treasury ministers
before compiling a report to be published before the summer recess.
Mr Nicholas Budgen, a Conservative member of the committee, says the MPs
involved begin the investigation with different, but strongly held
prejudices. 'Most of the Labour members believe that a good look at the
regulatory system will uncover the rottenness of the capitalist system.'
While not sharing such sentiments Mr Budgen, a rightwinger, will be probing
the witnesses to see whether existing regulations serve the market.
Mr John Watts, the Conservative chairman, has identified five main questions
that his committee will try to answer.
To what extent is self-regulation working? The decision of three leading
companies to oppose plans for the PIA, which is intended to act as the
self-regulating organisation for the retail financial sector, has infuriated
ministers.
Mr Jim Stretton, deputy managing director of Standard Life which has
withdrawn its support from the PIA, will argue that the present regulatory
structure was set up to accommodate self-regulation that has 'in practice
faded out of existence'. Mr Stretton, who is giving evidence to the
committee on March 9, says: 'I fear that in the short term the course of
regulation is set and that the PIA will come about. But I very much hope
that the committee will take the view that regulation has not reached its
long-term resting place.'
What is the cost of regulation? Mr Neil Hamilton, the DTI minister
responsible for de-regulation, has questioned whether the Financial Services
Act had not given rise to too much costly red tape.
For many Tory members this goes to the heart of the problem of trying to
roll back the boundaries of regulation without damaging the existing
regulatory structure.
Is it still appropriate for Lloyd's and the insurance industry to be
regulated by the Department of Trade and Industry? The Treasury has kept its
distance from this role for two main reasons.
First, the department did not want to 'take on more than it could chew', as
one official put it. Second, it has never liked the concept of being
directly responsible for regulation of an industry.
There is a strong body of opinion among some members of the committee that
the Treasury should take over responsibility for all regulation. For that
reason the MPs also question the Department of Social Security's
responsibility for pensions.
How will regulation on the Continent affect British consumers? Will
companies try to register in Luxembourg, for example, which has less
strenuous regulations than Britain, only to operate in the UK? Mr Watts says
his committee is concerned that there is no 'regulation arbitrage' in the
future.
Is the government co-ordinating regulation efficiently? The Home Income
Support Group, which is giving evidence today, has voiced its concern to Mr
Watts that there was no lead regulatory co-ordinator to turn to when people
lost out on investments.
Investment-linked home-income schemes were devised in the late 1980s as a
way for (mostly elderly) investors to unlock capital in their homes. Many of
the schemes were sold as 'safe' investments, with people unaware of the
risks.
'For all the Treasury's reluctance', says one senior member of the
committee, 'it would be surprising if it was not forced to take on an even
bigger regulatory role following our investigation.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
