<HEADLINE>
FT  16 FEB 94 / BBC plans to launch world service news channel in US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The BBC is planning to take its World Service Television News and
Information channel into the US for the first time in what will be seen as a
further challenge to Mr Ted Turner's Cable News Network.
Mr Bob Phillis, BBC deputy director general, said yesterday the corporation
hoped to launch the service, already available in more than 140 countries,
on US cable networks either late this year or early next.
Apart from news, the 24-hours a day channel would carry documentaries and
other factual programmes.
'This service would report international news and current affairs from an
international perspective in a way that complements the existing US
services,' Mr Phillis told the FT Cable and Satellite conference in London.
He said that the BBC hoped to launch its news and information channel in
Europe before the end of this year to complement the existing European
entertainment service.
He also said the BBC was: close to finalising an agreement to launch an Arab
language version of the BBC's news and information channel.
actively exploring the possibilities of launching new non-news channels and
news and information programmes in local languages as part of a more
aggressive commercial policy.
engaged in 'constructive talks' with News Corporation over whether BBC World
Service Television remained on the Star satellite system in Asia.
</TEXT>
