<HEADLINE>
FT  16 FEB 94 / Rail companies to pay Pounds 2.2bn for track use
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The private rail companies which take over the British Rail passenger
operations from next year can expect to pay about Pounds 2.2bn a year in
charges for the right to run their trains on the national rail network, the
government announced yesterday.
Mr John MacGregor, transport secretary, said these charges were 50 per cent
higher than the sums which BR charged in its own accounts, although BR did
not take into account items such as depreciation and a reasonable rate of
return.
The figures have been calculated on the assumption that Railtrack, the
company which will own and maintain rail track and signalling, will make a
5.6 per cent return on its assets, which have been valued at Pounds 6.5bn.
The Treasury requires the rate of return to rise to 8 per cent within four
years.
Mr Bob Horton, Railtrack chairman, said this return would be achieved by
improved efficiency and not by higher fares.
He added that higher track charges would not lead to any increase in fares,
reduction in services or the level of investment, currently Pounds 400m to
Pounds 500m a year, because they would be compensated for by an increase in
the public subsidy paid to the railway operators. The subsidy will rise from
Pounds 930m to Pounds 1.6bn. This would not lead to any increase in the
external financing limit of Pounds 1.26bn, Mr MacGregor said.
Increased corporation tax payments from Railtrack and BR and repayments of
government loans are to balance out the higher payments.
The level of track charges is a crucial element in the calculation that
potential bidders for rail franchises will make when assessing whether to
make a bid and the level of their bids.
Mr MacGregor said in answer to a parliamentary question: 'The new
arrangements establish for the first time the real cost of providing railway
infrastructure. Charges will be set in a transparent and commercially
realistic manner.'
But Labour yesterday warned that some services could be cut. Mr Brian
Wilson, opposition transport spokesman, said: 'What is the point of
massively hiking the track charges if the only result is that subsidy has to
be raised by a similar amount?'
Previously track costs could not be clearly identified from BR's accounts. A
precise calculation of costs based on the use of stations and electricity
and wear and tear of different services has made detailed figures possible.
Refinements in the figures will be made in the coming months, taking into
account possible changes in the levels of service provided by private rail
operators.
