<HEADLINE>
FT  16 FEB 94 / Labour attacks BAe over sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
British Aerospace came under fire at Westminster yesterday with more than 70
Labour MPs - including several frontbench spokesmen - expressing concern
about the company's decision to pay Pounds 3.2m to its retiring chairman.
The MPs - headed by Mr Derek Fatchett, a frontbench trade and industry
spokesman - used a parliamentary early day motion to claim that the
company's handling of the sale of Rover to BMW of Germany raised 'issues of
public concern'.
The motion said: 'That this House expresses its concern at the business
practices of British Aerospace which, having recently sold Rover to BMW, and
having made nearly 2,000 aerospace workers redundant in the last few weeks,
has now agreed to pay Pounds 3.2m to John Cahill, its retiring chairman and
United Kingdom tax exile, for two years' work; feels that these practices
raise issues of public concern; and condemns the prime minister for refusing
to answer questions about British Aerospace.'
