<HEADLINE>
FT  16 FEB 94 / BT set for trials of video scheme
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Telecom will officially confirm for the first time today that it is
pushing ahead with trials of its new video-on-demand system using ordinary
telephone lines.
BT will test the system which sends television pictures down telephone lines
to around 100 homes in Essex this spring.
Programmes are being provided for the experiment from a group of
organisations including the BBC, London Weekend Television, Kingfisher, the
retail group and Pearson, owner of the Financial Times.
Video-on-demand allows consumers to order programmes and films of their
choice from a central database. The extension of the system to the 24m homes
on BT's national telephone network would involve an investment of several
billion pounds.
If the spring experiment goes well BT will move to the next stage towards
the end of this year - a commercial experiment in the Colchester, Essex,
which could involve up to a quarter of a million homes.
At the same time BT plans to test video-on-demand with subscribers to
Westminster Cable, the telephone group's central London cable television
franchise.
The aim of the two experiments is to see whether there is a market for the
service before deciding on a national launch sometime next year.
The launch will probably be phased in over three or four years.
BT is confident after exploratory talks with most of the Hollywood studios
that it will be able to get access to the latest films. It hopes that the
studios will make films available for video-on-demand at the same time as
they become available in video shops.
</TEXT>
