<HEADLINE>
FT  16 FEB 94 / Car part groups seek know-how from Japanese
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Managing directors, team leaders and production workers from a dozen UK
motor component suppliers are to spend time in Japanese factories as part of
an initiative by the Department of Trade and Industry - backed by Nissan,
Toyota and Honda - to boost the competitiveness of the UK industry.
The aim of the two-year 'Learning from Japan' initiative, which is being
backed by Rover Group, Unipart Industries and the Inchcape group, is to
upgrade the quality of nearly 10,000 smaller component-makers in the UK.
Known as second- or third-tier suppliers, their products are built into the
more complex components systems supplied directly to the carmakers'
production lines by the few hundred first-tier component-makers such as GKN
and Lucas.
Together, components-makers form one of the biggest elements in the UK's
manufacturing economy, with turnover estimated at Pounds 14.7bn a year,
nearly 150,000 employees and Pounds 3bn in direct exports.
Improving the smaller companies' competitiveness is seen throughout the
industry as a vital step if the current revival of the UK-based - if no
longer UK-owned - motor industry is to be sustained.
A warning that it is already being put at risk by hundreds of small
suppliers failing to improve quality and productivity standards was given
recently by Prof Dan Jones, the motor industry academic who has been
involved in benchmarking studies between the Japanese and UK components
industries.
Prof Jones and other leading industry figures such as Mr George Simpson,
chairman of Rover Group who is shortly to take over as chief executive of
Lucas Industries, say that many of the biggest first-tier component-makers
have already learned from the standard-setting Japanese industry. According
to Mr Simpson, unless the big companies pass on these lessons many of the
smaller companies could disappear.
A benchmarking exercise comparing Japanese and UK suppliers undertaken by
Andersen Consulting, Cardiff Business School and Cambridge University 18
months ago found a two-to-one gap in productivity and a 100-to-one gap in
quality performance between Japanese and British suppliers, with only
Unipart matching Japanese suppliers on quality.
Andersen is also a partner in the DTI initiative. It has helped the
participating companies identify weak performance areas and after the
Japanese visits will help them develop improvement programmes.
The 12 companies taking part in the initiative range from small
pressings-makers such as Hockley-based Frederick Woolley to
plastics-moulders such as the Stadium group.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Nissan Motor.
    Toyota Motor Corp.
    Honda Motor.
    Rover Group.
    Unipart Industries.
    Inchcape.
</CO>
