FT  16 FEB 94 / Tories resist probe into auditing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Anthony Nelson, economic secretary to the Treasury, last night resisted
Labour demands for an inquiry into the auditing of companies.
Arguing against giving auditors a wider role in detecting fraud, he insisted
in a Commons debate that it would be wrong to turn them into 'snoopers and
narks'.
Mr Nelson stressed the importance of not undermining the relationship
between auditors and their clients, and of avoiding overlapping of the
responsibilities of auditors and the regulatory bodies in the financial
services sector.
MPs approved new regulations arising from the Bingham report on the events
leading to the collapse of Bank of Credit and Commerce International, which
impose a statutory duty on auditors to report relevant information to the
Bank of England and the regulatory authorities for building societies and
the insurance industry.
