<HEADLINE>
FT  16 FEB 94 / Midland backs down over cheque clearing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Midland Bank, one of the big four UK clearing banks, yesterday announced
that it would cut the time for processing customers' cheques and standing
orders.
Its statement came a day after Labour stepped up its attack on the high
street banks for delays in crediting customers' accounts.
Labour said that banks were making Pounds 300m a year from delays in
clearing customers' cheques and almost Pounds 40m a year from time spent
processing standing orders.
Midland's move increases pressure on Lloyds and National Westminster banks
to follow suit. This could add to a longer-term shift towards more explicit
charges to customers for particular services, as the scope for 'implicit
charges' is reduced.
Both banks said that the clearing cycle should be seen as part of the
competitive package of services being offered to customers.
At present, Barclays bank is the only UK clearer to pay interest on retail
deposits three days after they are made.
Midland also said that from mid-1995 it would give its personal customers 14
days' advance notice of money to be deducted from their accounts as charges
and interest.
The requirement to introduce pre-notification of charges was part of the
revised code of banking practice that was published last week. Subscribers
have until the end of 1996 to introduce pre-notification.
Midland added that from March 28 any standing order between customers at
different branches would be given value on the same day as the bank received
it.
Mr Nigel Griffiths, Labour's consumer affairs spokesman, said Midland's
announcement vindicated his campaign 'to get banks to treat customers more
fairly'. At the same time he urged it to give back to customers what he
described as its 'ill-gotten gains'.
He said: 'I want to know what has changed from the situation a fortnight
ago, when the bank claimed that they had no need to amend their rules.'
Mr Griffiths called for an inquiry by Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, and
for the two other UK clearers to act in a similar way to Barclays and
Midland.
Bankers do not expect the speeding up of the clearing process to produce
significant gains for individuals.
</TEXT>
