<HEADLINE>
FT  16 FEB 94 / Output fall sparks fears for recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A disappointing decline in manufacturing output in December yesterday raised
fears about the strength of the UK recovery.
Manufacturing output dropped 0.5 per cent between November and December
while industrial production as a whole fell 0.6 per cent, according to the
Central Statistical Office.
Both figures were much lower than analysts' forecasts. The CSO reduced its
estimate of the trend of annual growth in manufacturing output from 1.5 per
cent to 1 per cent.
However, the Treasury pointed out that the quarterly figures showed a
continuing upward trend.
Manufacturing output in the fourth quarter of last year was 0.5 per cent
higher than in the third quarter and 2.2 per cent higher than in the same
period a year earlier.
Industrial production was stronger than manufacturing output largely due to
the oil and gas industry.
UK oil and gas output reached a record level in December, and was 23.5 per
cent higher in the fourth quarter than in the last three months of 1992.
In the fourth quarter, industrial production was 1.3 per cent higher than in
the previous three months and 3.5 per cent higher than in the same period in
1992.
Over 1993 as a whole, industrial production was 2.7 per cent higher than in
1992, while manufacturing output rose 1.9 per cent.
A clearer picture of the strength of the recovery should be available today,
with the publication of statistics on unemployment, average earnings, retail
sales and the retail prices index.
Economists, however, also spotted some disturbing trends in the industrial
production figures. 'The breakdown of the data is unhelpful for the
government' said Mr Simon Briscoe of SG Warburg Securities. 'In the last
quarter, consumer goods production was up 1.6 per cent, while the output of
investment goods fell 1.5 per cent.'
The CSO blamed a number of factors for the December decline. Tobacco
production fell back after a one-off jump in November ahead of the Budget;
the iron and steel industries were affected by more holidays than normal;
computer production dropped back from higher levels earlier in the year; and
aerospace production continued to decline.
Electricity, gas and water output also fell back in December. This was
because the weather was slightly milder than normal but cold conditions in
October and November meant that, for the fourth quarter as a whole, the
sector's output rose by 1.7 per cent.
Mr David Coleman of the Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce said: 'The list
of excuses is suspiciously long and seasonal distortions should be adjusted
for. It is worrying that the latest fall in output was spread among several
industries.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
