FT  16 FEB 94 / Merger activity highest for two years
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mergers and acquisitions among UK companies have increased for the first
time in two years, according to figures published yesterday that bolster
government attempts to focus on economic recovery.
In the last quarter of 1993, companies spent a total of Pounds 2.7bn on
domestic takeovers compared with Pounds 1.2bn in the third quarter, the
Central Statistical Office said.
The increase pushed the annual value of mergers and acquisitions up to
Pounds 6.8bn, a 17 per cent rise over 1992.
Welcoming the signs of higher corporate activity, the Confederation of
British Industry said: 'This is a reflection of the growing confidence in
the recovery.'
The CSO said 160 deals were completed in the quarter. That figure was 51 per
cent ahead of the same period in 1992, reversing the downward trend for the
first time since the spring of 1991.
Mr Robert Hay, the CSO statistician who compiled the figures, added:
'Companies have got a bit more money to spend. Independent companies, in
particular, have proved very attractive for acquisitions.'
Relief at the figures was tempered, however, by the CSO's admission that
just three deals accounted for 62 per cent of the total spending on
takeovers in the last quarter.
Most of the increase resulted from the Pounds 800m acquisition of the Pillar
industrial businesses of RTZ, the mining company, by MB-Caradon, the
building products and security printing group. Scottish and Newcastle, the
brewing group, also made a substantial contribution to the total after
agreeing to pay Grand Metropolitan Pounds 622m for its Chef and Brewer pubs
subsidiary.
Whitbread, meanwhile, paid Pounds 260m for a 51 per cent stake in Whitbread
Investment Company, an associate group set up to protect regional brewers
from takeover.
However, deals worth less than Pounds 1m accounted for most of the
transactions that took place.
More than 200 small companies were either bought outright or merged into
larger operations last year, of which 69 changed hands in the last quarter -
the highest turnover for three years.
The CSO said acquisitive companies funded such deals mostly from existing
reserves, though they resorted to rights issues in 13 per cent of the
takeovers.
Databank Marketing Manager, Room 56/5, Central Statistical Office, Great
George Street, London SW1P 3AQ. 071 250 6081.
</TEXT>
