<HEADLINE>
FT  16 FEB 94 / Moscow to vet UN orders to its peacekeepers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD and PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Russian troops under United Nations command in the former Yugoslavia have
been told not to obey orders from their UN superiors until they are cleared
by Moscow, according to officials in President Boris Yeltsin's
administration.
This emerged as Mr Yeltsin raised strong objections yesterday to the threat
of air strikes against Bosnian Serbs in his first public comments on last
week's Nato ultimatum.
Presidential officials said at least one UN order to Russian troops had
already been countermanded. This was when Russian troops in eastern Croatia
refused an order to move nearer to Sarajevo.
Moscow's attitude was underlined by Russian deputy foreign minister Vitaly
Churkin. On his way back from a visit to Bosnia, he said it was unthinkable
that Russian troops should reinforce peacekeepers in Sarajevo while Moscow
was not part of the decision-making process in Bosnia.
Speaking after talks in Moscow with Mr John Major, the UK prime minister, Mr
Yeltsin warned Nato it would not succeed in ending the conflict without full
Russian agreement. But Mr Yeltsin held back from outright rejection of the
Nato ultimatum to the Bosnian Serbs to withdraw their heavy weapons from
around Sarajevo by midnight on Sunday or face air strikes.
The Russian president, who appeared angry at the precedent set by the west
in issuing a unilateral military warning, told journalists at the Kremlin:
'Some people are trying to resolve the issue on Bosnia without the agreement
of Russia. This will not succeed.'
But he did not explicitly demand that the UN Security Council pass another
resolution before launching military action. He also threw Russia's weight
behind efforts to lift the siege of Sarajevo.
He did, however, distinguish between air strikes in defence of UN forces -
which he approved - and the wider re-mit of the Nato decision. He warned the
west against trying to impose a solution to a conflict that could only be
ended at a negotiating table. 'Russia will take part actively in talks to
bring a peaceful solution. . . I am glad Mr Major supports our view on
that,' he said.
Mr Major, the first Nato leader to meet Mr Yeltsin since the ultimatum was
issued, was anxious to reassure his host. He told journalists: 'Before air
strikes proceed on this very limited front there would need to be a
reference back, under previously agreed Security Council resolutions, to the
secretary-general.'
Reinforcing his assurances after a dinner with Mr Yeltsin, he said he had
told the Russian leader the Nato ultimatum was not about generalised air
strikes nor was it a proposal to change the character of UN involvement.
London and Moscow had no difference on their objective in Bosnia, he added.
The aim was to get a negotiated settlement.
</TEXT>
