<HEADLINE>
FT  16 FEB 94 / US moves towards trade sanctions against Japan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE, JUREK MARTIN and MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The US yesterday moved towards trade sanctions against Japan by announcing
its conclusion that Japan had violated previous agreements to open its
domestic cellular phone market.
Mr Mickey Kantor, the US trade representative, said he would publish for
public comment within 30 days a list of proposed trade measures, not
necessarily to be limited to higher tariffs or other curbs on Japanese
cellular phone products sold in the US. 'This is a clear-cut and serious
case of a failure by Japan to live up to three agreements,' he said. The
agreements were negotiated in 1985-87, 1989 and finally, by letter, in 1992.
He said that new barriers had been raised after each fresh commit-ment.
Brandishing a cellular phone manufactured in the US by Motorola, he said it
was 'false and disingenuous' of the Japanese to accuse the company of not
trying hard enough. Motorola had only achieved 4 per cent of the Japanese
domestic market, not the 33 to 50 per cent promise held out.
Mr Christopher Galvin, chief operating officer of Motorola, said yesterday
that his company had lost an estimated Dollars 250m (Pounds 169m) and
Dollars 300m in annual sales because of the barriers which Japan appears to
have erected around the greater Tokyo cellular market. However, he hoped the
US would not have to impose sanctions against Japan. A trade war with Japan
would be counterproductive, he said.
The grace period of up to 30 days gives the US and Japanese governments time
to cobble together another agreement in this field. But should that fail,
other US actions now seem more likely. President Bill Clinton may announce
later this week his intention to revive the Super 301 trade law which, by
setting up deadlines for sanctions against 'unfair traders', would allow a
wide attack on Japan's perceived trade barriers.
The Motorola complaint has been long on the books and the timing of the US
finding is technically coincidental with the failure of last week's summit
to agree on specific ways of opening the Japanese market.
Nevertheless, US officials had warned it could well be the first indication
of the extent of the US displeasure with Japan. US officials say the
Motorola case illustrates the problems US companies face in penetrating
Japan's markets. Motorola is the world's largest manufacturer of cellular
telephones.
Michiyo Nakamoto adds from Tokyo: Japanese officials, ahead of the
announcement, appeared to regard the prospect of sanctions with equanimity.
One indicated that neither the possibility of sanctions nor the sharp
appreciation of the yen were cause for Japan to go back on its refusal to
accept the numerical targets sought by the US for a foreign share of its
markets. 'We made a decision at this point and that is where we stand,'
another official said.
The Bank of Japan intervened in foreign exchange markets to support the
dollar after the yen strengthened in Tokyo this morning to Y103.52. In New
York, the yen closed at Y103.815, slightly down on its London close of
Y103.1.
Hosokawa anxious, Page 6
The Japanese market, Page 19
Tokyo's sorry spectacle, Page 23
Bonds, Page 33; Currencies, Page 35; World stocks, Page 41
</TEXT>
