<HEADLINE>
FT  15 FEB 94 / FT Guide to the Winter Olympics (7): Age of the high-tech
mini-camera - Television Technology / On the ski slopes, a miniature
cable-car, running down rails parallel to the skier, gives vividly exciting
side-shots of the competitor leaning into bends as the landscape rushes by
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEITH WHEATLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Extraordinary technical effort goes into the creation of the Olympics on
television. For every well-groomed presenter, grinning affably across a
flower-laden coffee table, a dozen cameramen, sound recordists and unsung
heroes are out in the snow giving their all for the pictures on your screen.
Add to that the almost overwhelming complexity of the control rooms,
communications networks and graphics systems at the International Broadcast
Centre in Lillehammer and one understands why some old hands in sports
broadcasting still refer to the show as 'the daily miracle.'
Mainstream coverage at each event is the responsibility of NRK, the
Norwegian state broadcaster. However, TV activity at some centres is
delegated to partners with the depth of experience and innovative capacity
to manage the task.
At the luge and bobsleigh tracks, for example, the BBC is charged with
getting the pictures to billions of viewers. Although Britain's gentleman
Alpinists invented the bobsleigh at St Moritz, this is the first time the
BBC has attempted to cover snowland's equivalent of Formula One motor
racing.
'We've spent a lot of time learning and we anticipate having around 28
cameras to cover the two tracks,' said the BBC's executive producer Jim
Reside. 'With so many curves in the two runs, there are places where a
single camera can only catch the competitor for a second or two, but you
must have that shot.
'We've also been experimenting with a high-speed camera which will 'run'
down the track as the bob team accelerates.'
Other broadcasters have been running trials with the winter equivalent of
the miniature cameras mounted on Formula One race cars. Problems have
arisen, ironically, because of the extreme environmental care with which the
bob and luge tracks at Hunderfossen have been constructed.
The overhanging branches of the protected pine trees obscure and break up
the microwave links from the miniature camera to the helicopter overhead.
One possible alternative source of pictures is the blimp which CBS plans to
have overhead during the Games.
Equally radical are CBS plans for 'cap-cam' in the ice-hockey stadium. If
all teams agree, with the assent of the sport's ruling body, each goalkeeper
will have a miniaturised TV camera broadcasting from within his helmet.
Whether or not it will carry sound remains a secret. Perhaps now the
armchair hockey fan will discover what it is the goalkeepers say to
themselves while awaiting a penalty shot.
On the ski slopes, the viewer is promised the advent of yet another 'cam':
this time it is 'rail-cam'. A miniature cable-car, running down rails
parallel to the skier, gives vividly exciting side-shots of the competitor
leaning into bends as the landscape rushes by. It gives a sense of speed
undreamt of by the conventional camera looking up and down the hill.
At the ski-jump, a big concession has been made to the aesthetic
considerations of television. Producers and directors claimed that the
chairlift in the background, normally used to ferry competitors to the
summit, was ruining picture composition.
Following lengthy consultations, the chairs and cables will be removed for
the duration of the Games and competitors will be taken to the start line by
army lorry.
For the BBC, Lillehammer represents another significant technical first. Via
satellite, World Service Television will broadcast the BBC's version of the
Olympics to a considerable new audience outside the UK itself.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>British Broadcasting Corp.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>NOZ  Norway, West Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P4833 Television Broadcasting Stations.
</IN>
<XX>
