<HEADLINE>
FT  15 FEB 94 / FT Guide to the Winter Olympics (17): Parasites on the piste
 -International sponsorship / So-called 'ambush marketing' is the biggest
concern in the International Olympic Committee's commercial sector. It is
not a game but a deadly serious business
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEITH WHEATLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It is commonplace, whenever sport is discussed, to lament its increasing
'commercialisation'. Everyone likes to hark back to some imagined golden age
before sponsorships, advertising deals and player salaries featuring six
zeros. Such debates are almost as much fun as watching the sport.
Although the TOPIII sponsorship programme will raise the extraordinary sum
of about Dollars 800m for the Olympics in the quadrennium containing the
Lillehammer and Atlanta events, few people realise that Olympic sponsorship
is not new.
Even in the ancient Games, athletes received the backing of wealthy patrons.
When the modern Games were revived in Athens in 1896, the organising
committee faced financial hurdles and sold advertising in a souvenir
programme to help meet the bills. Among the companies taking space was
Kodak, still a leading Olympic sponsor through its participation in the
TOPIII programme.
When the Games visited Stockholm in 1912, rights were granted to several
Swedish companies to take exclusive photographs and sell memorabilia from
the Games. At Paris in 1924, advertising was sold within the main stadium.
This policy has since been reversed and the Olympics are now the only major
international sporting event with no signage at the actual venues.
Although the costs of becoming a TOPIII sponsor are such that only the
biggest multinational companies can take advantage of the global product
exclusivity on offer, the worries of the Olympic movement are now directed
as much to protecting existing partners as to seeking new ones.
'Ambush marketing' is the biggest concern in the International Olympic
Committee's commercial sector. 'It is not a game but a deadly serious
business. One that has the potential to destroy sponsorship,' says Michael
Payne, the IOC's marketing director. 'If ambush marketing is left unchecked
then the fundamental revenue basis of sport will be undermined.'
Unlike official sponsors, who pay significant amounts to help support the
Olympic Games, ambush marketeers pay nothing. In the words of Dick Pound,
unofficial commercial leader among the IOC vice-presidents: 'they try to get
a free ride, which is neither fair, ethical, nor right.' The phenomenon is
becoming known as 'parasitic marketing'.
The distinction is to try to correct the image of gung-ho Robin Hoods taking
from the wicked, wealthy corporate giants. In fact, the ambush tactics are
often adopted by companies bigger than the actual sponsors themselves.
Some of the most common ploys include creating signage or branding within
sight or broadcast of Olympic venues. Airships are a much-tried tactic. In
Barcelona, both Reebok and Fuji had blimps stationed to fly over the city
but these were grounded by IOC legal action.
For a decade, American Express has waged a guerrilla war to combat Visa's
status as an official Olympic sponsor. During 1988, Amex used photos of the
main Olympic stadium in Seoul for a general advertising campaign. Pictures
from the Asian games were retouched to make them look like the Olympics.
During the 1992 Winter Games in Albertville, Amex launched an entire print
advertising campaign in France based around the Games. The IOC successfully
sued the company.
'When a company chooses not to be involved with an event and then tries to
borrow or steal the imagery associated with that event, it steals from the
event and the institutions behind it,' says John Bennett of Visa
International.
So far in Lillehammer, most of the problems have been nipped in the bud
before lawyers become involved. However, Lillehammer Olympic Organising
Committee officials are watchful. Ethics are so highly developed in Norway
that any 'ambush' trouble is most likely to come from companies outside the
country.
'Very few Norwegian companies infringe on the rights of sponsors,' said
Asmund Berge of the organising committee. 'However, there have been some
examples of top international firms who have engaged in such activities. We
have had discussions with them and, so far, have been able to sort out the
matter.'
Dick Pound thoroughly disagrees with any advertising managers or marketing
managers who see ambush tactics as imaginative short-cuts for companies
short of resources.
'Cute? Street smart? You must be kidding,' says Pound. 'This is uncreative,
unethical and unprofessional.'
</TEXT>
