<DATE>940215
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 FEB 94 / FT Guide to the Winter Olympics (4): Turning Point for
Winter Games - Introduction / Norway has seized the opportunity to show that
the Olympics can be run by small communities representing a whole nation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEITH WHEATLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lillehammer represents a genuine turning point for the Winter Games and
possibly the Olympic movement as a whole. A change in timetable means that
Winter and Summer Olympics will now alternate every two years, rather than
being crowded into the same 12 months.
'The Winter events will now come into their own,' predicts IOC president
Juan Antonio Samaranch. 'They used to be seen as the Small Games before the
Big Games but now they will be seen as Olympics in their own right.
Lillehammer is the event of 1994.'
Norway has imaginatively seized the opportunity to show that the Olympics
can be run by small communities representing a whole nation. Lillehammer
embodies a 'small is beautiful' philosophy.
It says everything about the scale of this event that more than half the
population of Lillehammer could be accommodated in the Hakon Hall, where the
ice hockey finals will be played.
'Let us be proud of a small city and a small country's ability to take on
such a huge task as the Olympic Games,' said the community's mayor, Mr Audun
Tron, when he opened the Hakon hall.
Furthermore, Lillehammer has resolutely striven to stage the Games on its
own terms. Much of the luxury, excess and Byzantine protocol that has come
to surround the Olympics and its hierarchy simply has no place in Norwegian
culture - nor will it have.
'Some of the IOC members coming here will not be very happy,' predicted
Gerhard Heiberg, chief of the Lillehammer Olympic Organising Committee
(LOOC). 'There are no five-star hotels in Lillehammer and we won't be
building any.
'I said to Mr Samaranch at the beginning that the Games will be in Norway
and we want to do things in a Norwegian way - with modesty and nothing
especially luxurious.'
This focus on inherent qualities rather than external glitz has
characterised Lillehammer's programme, from the architecture through to the
hugely successful licensed goods programme.
Here again, Norwegian values set the tone in a sector that is notorious for
ephemeral trash mass produced in the Far East and peddled for a fast profit.
'I just told everyone No Junk. Your product must be unique in its way and
reflect our nation,' says Mr Heiberg.
But it is in the field of environmental development of the Olympics that
Lillehammer has set the pace. The LOOC agenda is described in detail later
in this magazine. The committee has used the Olympics to improve the
environment rather than accepting it as an ugly polluting monster, too
powerful to be turned aside. This has set the pattern for future Games.
Sydney based much of its detailed bid on the philosophies being put into
practice in Norway. Mr Samaranch and his team have advised any aspirant
Games city to learn from what is being done in Lillehammer.
The numbers of competitors and spectators will be higher than ever - not
least because of the passion with which the Norwegian public has taken the
Games to its heart.
Advances in television technology will ensure the best coverage is available
for Lillehammer's worldwide audience. Improved cameras and sound equipment -
and faster results systems - will enhance broadcasts.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>NOZ  Norway, West Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P794  Commercial Sports.
</IN>
<XX>
