<HEADLINE>
FT  15 FEB 94 / FT Guide to the Winter Olympics (12): The agony and the
ecstasy - Bobsleigh / You have as much influence on your direction, speed or
destiny as a stowaway on a space shuttle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ARNIE WILSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Riding a four-man bob as a helpless, ineffectual passenger clinging
desperately to the half-ton (when fully laden) steel and fibreglass machine,
you have as much influence on your direction, speed or destiny as a stowaway
on a space shuttle.
As the meat in the sandwich, you have no choice but to trust implicitly the
man in front (the driver) and the man at the back (the brakeman). Until the
1920s you would have encountered women bobsleighers too, but rather like the
Cresta Run, women are no longer officially allowed to compete
professionally. There is also an age restriction for men: you cannot race in
competitions if you are under 18.
If this were the real thing, the man normally sitting in your seat would
have a function: to 'Bob' backwards and forwards with the other two
rear-crew members. Hence the name. By leaning backwards at an extreme angle
and then snapping forward in unison, the Bobbers' action sharply accelerates
the speed of the sleigh.
The British invented bobsleighing, in St Moritz a century ago. After another
good World Cup year they are still a force to be reckoned with. It was in
1890 that two Britons tied two toboggans together and slid down the high
street, causing considerable commotion. To this day, St Moritz is one of the
few resorts where ordinary members of the public can try the four-man bob.
It is a nerve-racking experience. You and another apprehensive tourist
squeeze yourselves between the two professionals and pretend not to be
quaking with fear as the glistening but cumbersome contraption drifts -
agonisingly slowly at first - towards the first bend. So far, not too bad;
you tell yourself. Perhaps it will all be over so quickly you will not have
time to panic. No such luck.
Irrevocably, the monster gathers speed. Having survived the first bend, you
brace yourself for the next. No turning back now] You peep through your
tightly-clenched eyes just long enough to realise that the bends are coming
thicker and faster at impossible, almost vertical, angles. You feel as
though you are on a frozen wall of death. How can you possibly revert to the
horizontal again after flirting so brazenly with the vertical? Surely you
will hurtle helplessly into space at any moment]
When it is all over you have to pretend it was a breeze. With a casual grin
which belies your still pumping heart, you accept your certificate, signed
by Gunther Sachs - there has always been more than a hint of a playboy
element about the sport. The certificate comes complete with a photograph
taken on the way down to prove you have survived a minute or so of agony and
ecstasy. The ecstasy occurs when you stop.
St Moritz is one of the most celebrated 'natural' bobsleigh tracks built
each year out of snow. Cortina and Cervinia in Italy have other examples.
These natural tracks - which vary each year in design and speed - are
generally thought to be more intimidating and therefore a better test of a
good bobsleigher than the kind of artificial tracks found in Olympic
locations such as La Plagne, Igls, Lake Placid, Calgary and the track at
Hunderfossen to be used for the Games at Lillehammer. Most courses average
just over 1,300 metres.
The track at St Moritz is considered to be the fastest in the world,
rivalled only by the Mount Van Hoevenberg run in Lake Placid, New York, some
of whose 26 turns are more than 30 feet high, with walls that are almost
vertical.
According to the BBA (British Bobsleigh Association): 'A mixture of
strength, speed and driving ability is required' to be a successful
bobsleigher.
There is no mention of courage - perhaps that is unspoken, but without that
quality the other three are a little academic if you are chasing glory at
the highest level.
Racing sleighs have been known to clock speeds of up to 118mph although
between 60 and 70mph is more the norm.
Traditionally, what was formerly East Germany dominated bobsleighing. The
government there invested more than Pounds 10m in the sport over a period of
20 years and to this day, the most sought-after four-man sleighs come from a
factory in Dresden.
The standard model is almost 3.5m long, and runs on four steel runners which
are polished by hand to a mirror finish each day by the crews.
The sleigh's weight bearing down on the runners melts the ice at the point
of contact, and the sleigh actually runs on a thin film of water. The sleigh
costs more than Pounds 14,000 and even a set of runners can cost anything
from Pounds 2,000 to Pounds 8,000. According to the BBA 'There are no rich
men left in the sport - only sponsors and governments]'
The two-man version, at 3.1m long, is only a slightly less awesome mass of
hurtling steel, flesh and bone: the maximum weight with crew is almost 0.4
tonnes.
The British team - with Mark Tout performing exceptionally well and Sean
Olsson also getting good results in both the four-man and two-man events
last year - will be disappointed if they don't bring back a medal or two
from Lillehammer.
After my brief but terrifying encounter with the sport in St Moritz, I think
they deserve a medal just for completing the course.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>NOZ  Norway, West Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
