<PROFILE>_AN-EBRCXAHPFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940215
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 FEB 94 / FT Guide to the Winter Olympics (13): Why another US
miracle' is unlikely - Ice hockey / Norman de Mesquita takes a look at the
background to the Olympics event, and suggests which teams might earn a
medal in this year's tournament
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMAN DE MESQUITA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
I happened to be in New York on Friday February 22, 1980: that famous Friday
on which the United States, represented by a bunch of college kids, beat the
might of the Soviet Union at Lake Placid to come within one win of Olympic
gold.
The atmosphere in New York that Friday evening was very reminiscent of
London in 1966 when England had won football's World Cup. People who had no
regular interest in sport of any kind and who could not tell a hockey puck
from a red line, were caught up in the emotion of the event.
For the Americans, of course, it was very much a case of 'us against them'
and the win was seen as a triumph of democracy over what were seen as the
evils of communism.
Americans are very insular and generally care very little about
international sport. That is why the play-off between their two leading
baseball teams is known as the World Series' and why the team which wins the
National Basketball Association finals will be referred to as World
Champions'.
But success breeds interest and anything perceived as the best will arouse
interest as well. So the World Cup will give football a high profile in the
US, albeit temporarily.
In Winter Olympic terms, ice hockey is one of the very few events to arouse
the Americans' interest. The expansion of the National Hockey League (NHL)
to sunnier climes and the establishment of franchises in such unlikely
locations as Miami, Dallas and Anaheim means that the sport has a higher
profile than in the past and it is certainly followed more keenly than such
events as the luge or Nordic cross-country, which remain a closed book to
most Americans.
The non-availability of the best US players makes any chance of a repeat of
the Lake Placid 'miracle' unlikely. The same applies in Canada and, to a
lesser extent, in Sweden, the Czech Republic, Slovakia and Russia. Many of
the leading players now play for NHL teams and the league is reluctant to
close down for something like three weeks and make them available.
While basketball, a winter sport but part of the summer Olympics, can send a
'dream team' to represent the US, it is only for the occasional Canada Cup
that their ice hockey team can be at full strength.
Upsets are few and far between in Olympic ice hockey. Canada dominated the
event in its early days, with only Britain's controversial success at
Garmisch-Partenkirchen in 1936 interrupting their sequence of titles, from
1920 until 1952.
Then the Soviet Union came on the scene and brought a new dimension to the
sport in 1956 with the emphasis on the aesthetic qualities of ice hockey
rather than its physical excesses. The US sprang a surprise at Squaw Valley
in 1960, but Soviet domination returned from 1964 until Lake Placid in 1980.
Canada, in the meantime, withdrew from Olympic competition, objecting to
what they saw as the professionalism of the Soviet Union's 'amateurs.' But
they returned in 1980 and have taken part ever since.
Their chances of success this year are remote. For the World Championships,
which are held in the middle of April, a number of NHL players are
available, their teams having been eliminated from the play-offs. But this
is not the case at the end of February. Those players who have spent the
season with the Canadian national team are somewhat resentful of the arrival
of the top professionals in April and it is not conducive to team spirit.
There will be no such problems in Lillehammer, but it seems likely that
Canada together with the US, will field supporting players, rather than the
top stars.
For the first time, Russia will compete as an independent nation, which
means that, strictly speaking, there are no defending champions because the
1992 gold medal went to the Unified Team. Any Ukrainians or Latvians who
appeared in Meribel will not be in Lillehammer. And, for the first time in
Olympic competition, the Czech Republic could face Slovakia.
For Peter Stastny, a 13-year veteran of the NHL, it will be a dream come
true. When Slovakia beat Latvia in an Olympic qualifying tournament in
Sheffield last August, he described it as, 'the most exciting moment in my
life. It is far more exciting than playing for Quebec Nordiques in the
Stanley Cup play-offs or for Czechoslovakia in the world championships. This
time I am playing for my own country; a new country.'
Just as most of the best players in the Soviet and Unified teams were from
Russia, so most of the best Czechoslovakian players were Czech rather than
Slovakian. But Slovakia showed themselves to be some way ahead of Latvia in
the Sheffield tournament and this could be ominous news for the other
competing nations in Lillehammer.
Sweden, runners-up in 1992, will probably be a force once again, but it is
hard to look beyond Russia as the likely winners with the Czech Republic and
Slovakia as the probable dark horses.
The author is a London-based ice hockey writer and commentator
</TEXT>
<XX>
