<HEADLINE>
FT  15 FEB 94 / London Stock Exchange: Bar wars hit Foster'sfigures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE, PETER JOHN and JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A profits slide in Foster's, the Australian brewer which owns the Courage
drinks group, led to a sell-off among domestic beer stocks yesterday, though
they later recovered on the view that some of the selling may have been
overdone.
Analysts had expected Courage to produce flat profits at worse, but it fell
17 per cent. The brewer is the first of the industry leaders to include
figures for the crucial December sales period. While the market has been
fretting about a retail price war among bars and pubs, one analyst said the
Foster figures showed an intensifying of the wholesale battle between
brewers. 'Margin pressure on both fronts would be very worrying,' he said.
However, some in the market believe the brewery bears have gone too far, and
late yesterday there was talk of one leading broker preparing to turn
positive on selected stocks. After the initial hit yesterday, most shares
rallied. Bass fell 10, but recovered to close at 516p, down a net 3.
Whitbread slid 10 to 534p, after 530p, while Allied Lyons fell 7 to 612p.
Fosters was steady at 61 1/2 p. Grand Metropolitan gained 7 to 443p with one
broker recommending a switch out of Guinness, off 5 at 517p.
</TEXT>
