<HEADLINE>
FT  15 FEB 94 / International Capital Markets: Volume in interest rate swaps
advances 21%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The volume of interest rate swaps written during the first half of 1993
reached 60,553 contracts, up 21 per cent from the previous six months, while
contract volume in over-the-counter currency swaps dipped 8 per cent, to
4,897 contracts during the same period, according to a bi-annual survey of
swaps activity conducted by Arthur Andersen and commissioned by the
International Swaps and Derivatives Association.
ISDA said the total notional principal amount of new swaps written during
the first six months of 1993 reached Dollars 2,100bn, up 27 per cent from
the last six months of 1992. Interest rate swaps accounted for Dollars
1,900bn of the total, and currency swaps Dollars 157bn. The value of capital
risked in these transactions is typically 2 to 3 per cent of the notional
principal value.
The fastest-growing segment of the over-the-counter derivatives business,
according to the survey, was interest rate swap options, or 'swaptions.'
During the first half of 1993, about 40 per cent of interest rate and
currency swaps were denominated in US dollars.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
