<HEADLINE>
FT  15 FEB 94 / International Company News: Foster's up 21% in spite of
decline on brewing side
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT and TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Foster's Brewing Group, the Australian company which owns the Courage
business in the UK, reported a 21 per cent rise in profits after tax and
abnormal items in the half-year to end-December, to ADollars 210.8m
(USDollars 151m). This was on spite of lower earnings from its core brewing
interests,
Profits in the same period of 1992-93 stood at ADollars 173.6m. First-half
sales were ADollars 2.62bn, compared with ADollars 3.49bn.
The improvement, however, was due entirely to lower interest charges, which
fell from ADollars 123.6m to ADollars 89.3m, and a ADollars 49m abnormal
surplus related to asset sales, compared with a ADollars 17.7m gain in the
previous year.
By contrast, Foster's said its total brewing profit fell from ADollars
302.9m a year ago, to ADollars 279.8m. The Australian operations at Carlton
and United Breweries chipped in a 26.7 per cent improvement in operating
profits, at ADollars 129m, which Foster's said came on the back of increased
market shares - rising to 54 per cent of the Australian market overall in
December - and some product launches. Exports to Asia-Pacific and the Middle
East also grew 'significantly'.
In the UK, Courage saw earnings before interest and tax decline from
ADollars 131.3m to ADollars 100.7m. Although about ADollars 10m of this was
due to exchange rate movements, Fosters blamed most of the fall on higher
sales and marketing expenditure. Sales volume was static and market share
nudged ahead to just over 19 per cent.
Courage's performance was hampered by British consumers taking advantage of
relaxed excise duties to import cheap European beer. Courage - Britain's
second largest brewer - said it also expected Inntrepreneur Estates, its pub
joint venture with Grand Metropolitan, to break even in 1994 despite an an
Pounds 18m (USDollars 263m) loss in the 12 months to September 30 last year.
In Canada, meanwhile, the contribution from Molson fell from ADollars 69.8m
to ADollars 50.2m. However, Foster's said around ADollars 14m of this
reflected the change in ownership structure, which saw the Australian
group's stake fall from 50 to 40 per cent.
After the lower interest charges - which reflected the ongoing disposal
programme at Foster's and associated reduction in the group's heavy debt
levels - pre-tax operating profits were 13.3 per cent higher at ADollars
178.3m.
Foster's said the economic outlook in its main markets of Australia, the UK
and Canada, was improving.
</TEXT>
