<HEADLINE>
FT  15 FEB 94 / International Capital Markets: Matif aims to win forex
business from OTC rivals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Matif, the French futures exchange, hopes to wrest business from the
over-the-counter foreign exchange markets when it opens options contracts on
price movements between the US dollar and two European currencies on May 20.
In launching the forex options the exchange will be defying the overwhelming
sentiment of the world's foreign exchange traders: that exchange-listed
currency hedging vehicles are redundant.
With a daily global net turnover in excess of Dollars 880bn, forex dealers
have deep and liquid markets in which to transact both spot business and
contracts for forward delivery. These unregulated markets allow a
flexibility in transaction size and delivery terms that other exchanges have
been unable to imitate.
The Chicago Mercantile Exchange was the first to attempt to divert some of
the lucrative forex turnover on to its trading floor in 1972. It added
options on its currency futures in 1984, and in 1993 had currency-related
turnover of 5.9m contracts. The growth has been respectable, exchange
officials say, but has not kept pace with the overall expansion in global
forex dealings.
London's Liffe listed options on spot foreign exchange rates in 1985, but
abandoned the effort in 1990, unable to compete with deeply liquid and
highly standardised OTC markets. The Chicago Board Options Exchange tried
similar products, but volume was so low that they transfered the business to
the tiny Philadelphia Stock Exchange.
Matif's options contracts - one reflecting dollar/D-Mark exchange rates and
the second dollar/French franc movements - most closely resemble those
traded in Philadelphia. Franc and D-Mark options are the Philadelphia
markets' most active currency products. In January, Philadelphia's average
daily volume in spot D- Mark options was 15,000 contracts, and in its French
franc options, 12,200 contracts.
Matif officials reason that Philadelphia is an unlikely centre for foreign
exchange derivatives. They also have discovered that a good portion of
Philadelphia's currency options business originates in Paris, and they would
like to recapture it, however small.
The Matif's options contracts, to be sized in Dollars 100,000 increments,
will be traded on Matif's floor during regular business hours, and on its
old THS telephone trading system after hours.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>FRZ  France, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
<XX>
