<HEADLINE>
FT  15 FEB 94 / International Company News: Cigna warns on cost of LA
earthquake
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Cigna, the US insurer, reported a fall in after-tax profits last year as it
took a Dollars 244m charge to cover asbestos and environmental costs. It
also restructured its property and casualty operations.
The company said it would report after-tax losses of Dollars 60m in the
current quarter, due to the Californian earthquake, and Dollars 25m
attributable to the severe weather in the US.
However, Mr Wilson Taylor, chief executive, said the restructuring on the
property and casualty side, which led to a Dollars 107m after-tax charge,
would lead to improved results in the future.
Net income for the year fell to Dollars 234m, or Dollars 3.25 a share, from
Dollars 311m, or Dollars 4.34, in 1992. In the final three months of 1993,
net income jumped to Dollars 194m from Dollars 50mm, boosted by after-tax
realised investment gains of Dollars 102m, compared with Dollars 19m in the
1992 quarter.
Operating income in Cigna's life and health insurance businesses was up 42
per cent during the year, to Dollars 464m.
Property and casualty activities reported an operating loss of Dollars 124m
in the final quarter, and Dollars 350m in the year as a whole, compared with
losses of Dollars 115m and Dollars 351m.
</TEXT>
