<HEADLINE>
FT  15 FEB 94 / International Company News: Mexican group to pay Dollars
708m for hotel chain
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAMIAN FRASER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MEXICO CITY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Japanese company Aoki Corporation has agreed in principle to sell the
Westin Hotel &amp; Resort chain for Dollars 708m to a group of investors led by
Bernardo Dominguez, the chief executive of DSC, a large Mexican business.
The Aoki Corporation bought Westin Hotel &amp; Resort in 1988. The chain
operates more than 70 luxury hotels in 19 countries. It has around 42,000
rooms, and reported revenues of about Dollars 420m a year.
Mr Dominguez and investors will buy about 50 of the hotels, with those in
Asia, six in Canada, and some minority investments in the US remaining in
the hands of the Aoki Corporation. The two companies will sign agreements
co-ordinating services, marketing and sales to ensure the Westin group
operates as an integrated organisation.
DSC is a privately-owned company with interests in construction, property
and tourism. It owns several four-star hotels in Mexico, and one of the
country's largest travel agencies and tour operators.
Mr Pablo Macedo, head of DSC's tourism group, said the new owner would
expand the Westin hotel chain in Europe and Latin America. He said DSC would
not run the Westin hotel group, but that Mr Dominguez, as chairman of the
board, would play an important part in overseeing its operations.
The letter of intent to conclude the transaction was signed between the two
groups at the weekend. The transaction is expected to be finalised in the
second quarter of 1994, according to a joint statement by Aoki and Mr
Dominguez. Aoki was advised by The Blackstone Group of the US, and Mr
Dominguez by Salomon Brothers.
</TEXT>
