<DATE>940215
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 FEB 94 / International Company News: US groups agree breast implant
deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Three US healthcare groups have agreed to provide more than Dollars 3bn
between them for a proposed world-wide compensation fund for women who have
suffered ill health as a result of silicon breast implants.
The companies announced last year that they were seeking to negotiate such a
deal.
Dow Corning, Bristol-Myers Squibb and Baxter International said they had now
reached agreement between themselves, and with representatives of claimants,
that would lead to the three bearing 80 per cent of the Dollars 4bn
settlement costs over the next 30 years.
The settlement is intended to benefit women around the world who have
already suffered illnesses, or who become ill in future. However, lawyers in
the US said that the bulk of the settlement would go to women in that
country.
'Like all settlements, this is a political solution - these companies are
based in the US and have most of their business here,' said Ms Lori Henkel,
a lawyer in Rochester, New York, who represents around 150 claimants.
All women with implants will be included in the deal automatically, and will
lose their right to sue the implant manufacturers, unless they actively opt
out.
This aspect of the arrangement is likely to come under particular scrutiny
by the district court in Birmingham, Alabama, where all the implant cases
have been consolidated. The court must approve the terms of the settlement
for it to take effect.
The settlement would be threatened if a large number of women decided to opt
out. In that case, Bristol-Myers said it would withdraw from the deal. Women
who have suffered cosmetically from implants are believed to fare worst
under the deal, and so are the most likely to reject the offer.
All three companies reported one-off charges in the final quarter of 1993 in
anticipation of the settlement. Bristol-Myers said yesterday the present
value of the future payments it expected to make under the settlement was
Dollars 1.15bn, out of a total Dollars 1.5bn costs associated with implant
claims. Of this, at least Dollars 1bn was covered by insurance, it said.
Dow Corning put its total contributions to the fund at Dollars 2bn over the
next 30 years. It announced a pre-tax charge of Dollars 640m for the fourth
quarter, after expected recoveries under insurance policies. Baxter said the
settlement would cost it Dollars 556m, of which Dollars 426m would be
covered by insurance.
</TEXT>
<XX>
