<HEADLINE>
FT  15 FEB 94 / International Company News: Ford to increase stake in Hertz
to 54%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ford, the US motor vehicle manufacturer, is planning to increase its stake
in Hertz, the world's largest vehicle rental company, to 54 per cent.
Ford said that it is to take over the 5 per cent stake held by Commerzbank
of Germany, which made the first approach to Ford to dispose of the holding.
None of the financial details of the deal have been disclosed.
Hertz is currently 49 per cent owned by Ford, while Volvo, the Swedish
vehicle maker holds a 26 per cent stake and 20 per cent is controlled by
Hertz management.
The car rental group is the largest single private purchaser of new vehicles
in the US. It has a domestic rental fleet of around 230,000 vehicles and a
worldwide fleet of 420,000.
Vehicle makers have established dominant positions in most of the world's
leading vehicle rental groups in recent years, and Hertz already plays a key
role for Ford as its biggest single private customer.
Around 70 per cent of Hertz's vehicle purchases in the US are from Ford,
while the US carmaker supplies a third of Hertz's fleet in Europe.
Last year Hertz marginally improved its net income to Dollars 53m from
Dollars 51m on a turnover of Dollars 2.85bn compared with Dollars 2.82bn a
year earlier.
Ford first acquired an 80 per cent stake in Hertz at the end of 1987, when
it assisted the vehicle rental group's management to purchase the company
from UAL (Allegis Corporation) for Dollars 1.3bn.
Ford said at the time that it planned to expand the ownership base in order
to reduce its holding to a minority position, and it later sold stakes to
both Volvo and Commerzbank.
The US vehicle maker said yesterday that it had obtained all the necessary
US regulatory approvals to return to a majority position in Hertz, and that
it expected the deal to be approved by the European Commission.
The Commission said yesterday that it may investigate the deal and
competitors must file their submissions by February 22.
</TEXT>
