<PROFILE>_AN-EBODHAEQFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940215
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 FEB 94 / UK Company News: Lower interest charges boost WHC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Pre-tax profits at Westminster Health Care, the nursing home group, jumped
from Pounds 1.6m to Pounds 5.2m for the six months to November 30, partly
thanks to lower interest charges following the group's flotation last year.
Net interest costs were Pounds 310,000 (Pounds 2.74m). Earnings per share
were 8.6p (5.4p) and the interim dividend is set at 1.75p.
Mr Patrick Carter, chief executive, said that after 10 months working with
the new Community Care legislation, it was taking longer to fill beds in
existing and new homes; but he said this had been anticipated, and WHC had
held back opening new homes during the first half.
The effect was marginal, with 57 per cent of revenue coming from non-social
services budgets. The rule changes had led to differential pricing for
state-funded residents, which now ranged from Pounds 280 a week - the old
social security rate - to Pounds 400 plus in areas such as London.
During the half year 186 beds were added, taking the total to 3,429, and
with a further 581 due to come on stream in the second half there would be
4,010 by the May year end.
Plans were in place to increase this to 5,000 by the end of its 1995 year.
The group is testing a new business, running an acute surgery unit in Devon
performing operations for the National Health Service.
The unit had been acquired from the receivers in November and was being
assessed to see whether returns would justify investment.
Mr Carter said the changes in the nursing home business, which had increased
the private sector's provision of beds, would probably be repeated in
surgery. This could provide a growth area when nursing homes began to
mature.
Turnover rose 41 per cent to Pounds 23.9m (Pounds 17m) for pre-interest
profits up 26 per cent to Pounds 5.48m (Pounds 4.34m).
Mr Kent Phippen, finance director, said the squeeze on margins reflected
higher costs associated with being a quoted company, the slower fill rate
and an upgrading of the computer system needed to deal with a range of local
authority purchasers rather than with the DSS.
Mr Phippen said gearing at 23 per cent was lower than expected. Cashflow
funded more than half the Pounds 10.4m spent on fixed assets.
COMMENT
The shares have performed well since the float at 260p last April. Since
then a number of other operators have come to market fostering the idea that
nursing homes provide a sure route for profit growth. But, as Sir Jimmy
Goldsmith said, if you spot a bandwagon you have missed it. Greater stock
selectivity is now creeping into the sector. WHC has proved itself to be one
of the winners in operational terms, and it is encouraging to see it testing
a related business without indulging in great expense. One concern might be
that National Medical Enterprises, which retained a 42 per cent stake after
the float, might one day want to sell just when WHC needs to raise further
capital for expansion. Meanwhile, on forecasts of about Pounds 11.3m for the
year, against Pounds 4.3m, the prospective p/e approaches 21. No longer a
compelling buy, but unlikely to disappoint in the medium term.
</TEXT>
<XX>
