<HEADLINE>
FT  15 FEB 94 / Time to capitalise on a classy set of connections
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Whom you know is very important in the French corporate scene and there can
be few people better connected than Mr Jacques Friedmann.
Mr Friedmann, 61, is a former chairman of Air France and a close friend of
both favourites for the conservative candidacy in next year's presidential
elections, Mr Jacques Chirac, mayor of Paris, and Mr Edouard Balladur, prime
minister. Yet he will need all his valuable contacts in his new role as
chairman of Union des Assurances de Paris (UAP), the next company to be sold
in the French privatisation drive.
The completion of the sale of the government's stake in Elf Aquitaine, the
oil group, clears the decks for the sale of the state's 50 per cent UAP
holding, which could be worth FFr25bn-FFr28bn. Mr Friedmann, after only
three months at UAP, faces the challenge of steering France's largest
insurer and biggest institutional investor into the private sector.
He is adamant that it is ready for sale. 'Of course we're ready,' he said in
an interview with the FT at his elegant office at UAP's headquarters on
Place Vendome in Paris. 'Is there any reason why we shouldn't be?'
The analysts who follow UAP are less enthusiastic. Its net profits fell from
a peak of FFr4.2bn in 1990 to FFr1.08bn in 1992. Mr Friedmann recently
warned that it only managed a modest recovery to FFr1.5bn in 1993. Banque
Worms, its troubled banking subsidiary, is still in the red.
The French insurance market is still beset by recession. UAP, like other
state controlled insurers, is burdened by heavy overheads. It also has to
digest its latest acquisition - a controlling stake in Colonia, the big but
battered German insurer.
'What we really want is firm evidence that UAP is tackling its long-term
profitability problem, and that will involve some difficult decisions about
costs,' said one analyst. 'It also needs a clear international strategy.
It's all very well buying businesses, but it has to prove it can run them.'
Mr Friedmann insists that UAP will deliver on both counts. One of his
priorities is to modernise the huge domestic network. He does not, however,
envisage doing so by shedding staff. Instead he hopes to improve
productivity through investment in technology and by drumming up new
business.
Where does he expect to find new business in the intensely competitive
French insurance market? 'From the reform of the state pension and health
insurance systems,' he replied. 'These reforms will create huge new markets
and the big insurers like UAP are best placed to benefit.'
How can he hope to compete against the UK and US insurers, which have had
more experience in the pensions sphere and see it as an entree into the
French market? 'We have excellent contacts with large French companies.
They've been coming to us for years for big commercial policies and they'll
come for their employee pension plans.'
On the international front Mr Friedmann plans to expand UAP's activities
outside Europe, which now account for just 3 per cent of turnover. 'There
are lots of markets, particularly in Asia, that are only just opening up,'
said Mr Friedmann, who recently acted as Mr Balladur's intermediary in a
successful effort to reopen commercial relations with China.
His plans for expansion in Europe are more modest. UAP is interested in
acquiring a damage insurer in the UK, although he declined to comment on
speculation about talks to acquire The Provincial. In the meantime he plans
to restructure UAP's European network, which includes Royal Belge in Belgium
and Sun Life in the UK as well as Colonia.
</TEXT>
