<HEADLINE>
FT  15 FEB 94 / UN backs Nato over Bosnian air strikes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY and MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The United Nations Security Council yesterday threw its weight behind the
Nato threat to launch air strikes around Sarajevo if Bosnian Serb and
Bosnian government troops fail to place their artillery under UN
supervision.
Security Council members sent a clear message to the Serbs during a debate
that the UN meant to act in total unison with Nato.
US ambassador Ms Madeleine Albright told the Security Council: 'Co-operation
between Nato and the UN is essential - not only for the citizens of Sarajevo
and other safe areas in Bosnia, but also for the precedent it will set for
the future of collective security.'
The statement came as the British commander of the United Nations Protection
Force (Unprofor) in Sarajevo said he had no doubt that by the time the
ultimatum was up the Serbs would have complied totally with the weapons
demand.
But Lieut Gen Sir Michael Rose told reporters that he would have 'no
hesitation' in calling in airstrikes after the ultimatum expired if they
were warranted.
Nato has said it will strike at positions held by either Serbs or Bosnian
government troops if heavy weapons located in the exclusion zone are not
handed in by midnight GMT on Sunday.
Last night, French Prime Minister Edouard Balladur reaffirmed that there
would be no extension of the Nato ultimatum. Mr Balladur told France-2
television: 'The ultimatum will not be extended by a day.'
Earlier, Gen Jean Cot, the French commander, admitted there were very few
weapons being handed over despite attempts by UN forces to speed up their
collection so that Nato air strikes would not be necessary.
Sir Michael has already spoken to senior Nato officials about the need for
much greater back-up on the ground to collect and supervise heavy weapons.
He acted to quash reported differences between Nato and UN officers over
what constitutes UN control over the Serb weapons.
Sir Michael Said: 'Nato and the United Nations are completely aligned as to
what our plans are.'
</TEXT>
