<HEADLINE>
FT  15 FEB 94 / Bosnians slow to hand arms to UN
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY and MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The number of artillery pieces being placed under United Nations supervision
by Bosnian Serb and Bosnian government troops is 'negligible', a senior UN
officer said yesterday.
General Jean Cot of France admitted that there were very few weapons being
handed over despite attempts by UN forces to speed up their collection in
order to pre-empt Nato air strikes on positions near the city.
UN officials believe air strikes could lead to an escalation of the fighting
and undermine the humanitarian relief effort, and could amount to a Nato
declaration of war against Serbia.
General Sir Michael Rose, the British commander of the United Nations
Protection Force (Unprofor), has spoken to senior Nato officials about the
need for much greater back-up on the ground to collect and supervise heavy
weapons.
Mr Vitaly Churkin, Russian deputy foreign minister, warned that if Sarajevo
were not demilitarised, 'an air strike is unavoidable and this could cause a
further escalation of the war'. He was speaking at a news conference in
Skopje, the capital of Macedonia, the former Yugoslav republic.
Nato has said it will strike at any positions, held by either side, if heavy
weapons located in the exclusion zone are not handed in by midnight GMT on
Sunday.
Military experts yesterday said the UN was at a disadvantage in trying to
demilitarise Sarajevo since it did not know exactly how many weapons were
held by either side. 'There are certain kinds of weapons which we can
identify from the air. But there is no inventory. We do not know where all
the weapons are,' said Mr Edward Foster, military strategist at Britain's
Royal United Services Institute.
There is also concern that Bosnia's Serb forces are placing weapons in their
own depots to be supervised by unarmed UN personnel. Weapons handed in by
the Bosnian government are being supervised by Ukrainian UN peacekeepers. UN
officials are also concerned that the Bosnian government forces might try to
destabilise the ceasefire by provoking the Serbs, possibly leading to Nato
air strikes.
</TEXT>
