<HEADLINE>
FT  15 FEB 94 / Arts: The Royal Academy plans a feast of Old Masters
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Royal Academy is getting back to basics with a vengeance; its 1994-95
programme, announced yesterday, is a feast of Old Master art.
It starts in March with Goya, concentrating on his small paintings; picks up
steam in September with a major exhibition of 18th century Venetian art,
packed with Tiepolos, Canalettos, Guardis and Canovas, and continues a month
later with The Painted Page, illustrations from Italian Renaissance books
and manuscripts; and reaches its apogee next January with the first major
Poussin show for decades, with over 90 paintings by the 17th century French
artist.
Tucked in between are displays of art from late 19th century Belgium; the
Summer Show; and in February 1995 an architectural exhibition devoted to
Lord Burlington and the Palladian style.
It is chance rather than design which has eliminated the modern from the
programme. The RA is on something of a high at the moment, with a small, but
unexpected, Pounds 150,000 surplus on its 1993-94 operations. But it is
finding it harder to get sponsors, and even the Goya show lacks a backer.
Its corporate membership has fallen from 161 to 141 but this shortfall has
been made good by signing up 5,000 more Friends. With 68,000 in the club the
RA is third in the world, (behind the Los Angeles County Museum and the
Metropolitan Museum, New York), in the size of its Friends organisation.
The recession also hit the Summer Show, with visitors down 10 per cent at
135,501, and the value of art sold, at Pounds 1m, is nearly 50 per cent
lower than the 1990 peak.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
