<HEADLINE>
FT  15 FEB 94 / BR signal staff seek 11% pay increase
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Rail signalling staff are demanding an immediate interim 11 per cent
basic pay increase in return for improved productivity in recent years.
Unless the claim is met, their union - the RMT - says it will refuse to
negotiate a restructuring agreement for signalling staff with BR. 'We have
an overwhelming case for an immediate down payment', said RMT last night.
Union leaders have submitted their proposal and BR is expected to reply
shortly.
In a letter to RMT branches, the union's general secretary Mr Jimmy Knapp
says BR has 'obtained significant productivity from its signalling grades,
but their rates of pay have remained unacceptably low in their own right and
even more so when compared to other BR grades and London Underground
signalling staff.' The RMT argues the number of signalling staff has fallen
by 35 per cent since 1980 and new equipment and responsibilities have been
introduced without any compensating cash reward.
The union says signalling staff work an average 52.4 hours a week for a a
basic Pounds 124 to Pounds 137. Average weekly earnings including overtime
are between Pounds 248 and Pounds 268.
